      "snippet": "Disease:\nBlepharophimosis, ptosis, and epicanthus inversus syndrome (BPES)\n\nGenetics:\n- Causative gene: FOXL2  \n- Inheritance pattern: Autosomal dominant  \n\nKey Phenotypes:\n- Blepharophimosis (horizontal narrowing of the palpebral fissures)  \n- Ptosis (usually bilateral, severe)  \n- Epicanthus inversus (fold curving from lower lid medially upward)  \n- Telecanthus (increased distance between medial canthi)  \n- Distinctive facial features:\n  - Broad nasal bridge  \n  - Low-set ears  \n  - Short philtrum (shortened distance between nose and upper lip)  \n\nDifferentiating Features:\n- Combination of blepharophimosis, severe bilateral ptosis, and epicanthus inversus present from birth.  \n- Telecanthus with relatively normal interpupillary distance (vs true hypertelorism in other craniofacial syndromes).  \n- Characteristic midface features (broad nasal bridge and short philtrum) co-occurring with the eyelid malformation complex.  \n- Low-set ears in association with the above ocular configuration can help separate BPES from isolated congenital ptosis or simple telecanthus.\n\nHallmark(s):\n- Classic triad: blepharophimosis + ptosis + epicanthus inversus.  \n- Telecanthus with the above triad is highly characteristic.\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- No obligate structural eye globe anomalies (the primary defect is eyelid configuration rather than globe malformation).  \n- Absence of true orbital hypertelorism despite apparent wide-set inner canthi.\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Congenital, bilateral blepharophimosis with severe ptosis and epicanthus inversus, plus telecanthus, in a patient who also has a broad nasal bridge, low-set ears, and a short philtrum, strongly points to BPES over other ptosis or craniofacial syndromes."
    },
