      "content": "[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: Kaufman oculocerebrofacial syndrome (Blepharophimosis-ptosis-intellectual disability syndrome)\n\nGenetics: UBE3B (E3 ubiquitin protein ligase); autosomal recessive\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Severe intellectual disability  \n- Cranial shape abnormalities: brachycephaly, microcephaly  \n- Ocular/facial features: blepharophimosis, ptosis, upslanting palpebral fissures, nystagmus, other eye abnormalities  \n- High / highly arched palate  \n- Muscular hypotonia  \n- Constipation  \n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s): \n- Combination of blepharophimosis with ptosis and upslanting palpebral fissures in the setting of severe intellectual disability  \n- High / highly arched palate with characteristic oculofacial anomalies  \n- Autosomal recessive UBE3B-related oculocerebrofacial syndrome\n\nKey Negative Finding(s): \n- Not specified in the text\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Severe intellectual disability + brachycephaly/microcephaly + blepharophimosis/ptosis with upslanting palpebral fissures + high palate + hypotonia and nystagmus  \nThis tightly linked oculocerebrofacial triad (distinctive eyelid/palpebral fissure anomalies, cranial dysmorphism, and marked neurodevelopmental impairment) strongly points toward Kaufman oculocerebrofacial syndrome among syndromic intellectual disability disorders.",
      "disease_name": "KAUFMAN OCULOCEREBROFACIAL SYNDROME; KOS"
    },
    {
      "title": "1p36 deletion syndrome",
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1p36_deletion_syndrome",
      "content": "[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: 1p36 deletion syndrome (monosomy 1p36)\n\nGenetics: Deletion on chromosome 1p36; Inheritance pattern: Not specified (typically de novo cytogenetic deletion, but not stated in text)\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Moderate to severe intellectual disability  \n- Global developmental delay (speech and motor)  \n- Severely limited or absent speech  \n- Hypotonia (present in almost all children)  \n- Seizures/epilepsy (approximately half)  \n- Structural brain abnormalities (e.g., agenesis of corpus callosum, cerebral cortical atrophy, ventriculomegaly, gait abnormalities)  \n- Behavioral problems (temper outbursts, object throwing, striking people, screaming, self-injury such as wrist biting and head banging)  \n- Autism spectrum features and stereotypies  \n- Failure to thrive and delayed growth  \n- Feeding difficulties (dysphagia, esophageal reflux, other feeding problems)  \n- Hearing impairment (mentioned globally in initial description)  \n- Vision impairment, including hypermetropia, myopia, and strabismus  \n- Distinct facial features (not further specified in the text)  \n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):  \n- Deletion localized specifically to chromosome 1p36 (outermost band of the short arm of chromosome 1)  \n- Combination of severe speech impairment (often only a few words or none) with global developmental delay and hypotonia  \n- High frequency of structural brain anomalies (especially agenesis of the corpus callosum) along with seizures  \n- Prominent behavioral dysregulation including self-injurious behaviors and autism spectrum features in the setting of a known terminal 1p36 deletion  \n\nKey Negative Finding(s):  \n- Not specified in the text  \n\nUnique Constellation:  \n- Global developmental delay with particularly severe speech impairment  \n- Almost universal hypotonia plus feeding difficulties (dysphagia, reflux, failure to thrive)  \n- Structural brain anomalies (especially corpus callosum agenesis, cortical atrophy, ventriculomegaly) with epilepsy  \n- Behavioral abnormalities (self-injury, temper outbursts, autism spectrum traits)  \n- Coexisting hearing and vision impairment  \n- Occurring in the context of a cytogenetically demonstrable 1p36 deletion  \n\nThis combination, especially severe speech limitation + hypotonia + characteristic brain malformations + behavioral/autism features + 1p36 deletion, strongly points toward 1p36 deletion syndrome over other intellectual disability and epilepsy syndromes.",
      "disease_name": "CHROMOSOME 1p36 DELETION SYNDROME, DISTAL"
    },
    {
      "title": "Tubulin alpha-1A chain",
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tubulin_alpha-1A_chain",
      "content": "[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: TUBA1A-related tubulinopathy (TUBA1A-associated brain malformation syndrome)\n\nGenetics: TUBA1A, autosomal dominant (typically de novo)  \n*(Inheritance not explicitly stated in the passage; provided based on established clinical knowledge.)*\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Malformations of cortical development (e.g., lissencephaly, pachygyria, polymicrogyria-like cortical dysplasia)  \n- Abnormal neuronal migration  \n- Abnormal neuronal maturation and axonal process formation  \n- Structural brain anomalies, often including:  \n  - Abnormal corpus callosum  \n  - Ventriculomegaly  \n  - Brainstem and/or cerebellar hypoplasia or dysplasia  \n- Developmental delay and intellectual disability (implied by neuronal migration/maturation defects)  \n- Neurologic impairment (e.g., seizures, hypotonia) secondary to brain malformation\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n\n- Cortical malformations tightly linked to a primary defect in \u03b1-tubulin (TUBA1A), a major fetal brain tubulin highly expressed in morphologically differentiated neurologic cells  \n- Strong involvement of neuronal migration and process extension, reflecting disruption of microtubule dynamics in neurodevelopment  \n- Brain malformations that often combine cortical dysgenesis with commissural, ventricular, and posterior fossa anomalies in a \u201ctubulinopathy pattern\u201d\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n\n- Not specified in the provided text.\n\nUnique Constellation:\n\n- A combination of:  \n  - Malformations of cortical development  \n  - Defects in neuronal migration and process extension  \n  - Widespread structural brain anomalies (corpus callosum, ventricles, brainstem/cerebellum)  \n  in the setting of a pathogenic variant in TUBA1A (a fetal-brain\u2013predominant \u03b1-tubulin), strongly points toward a TUBA1A-related tubulinopathy rather than other causes of lissencephaly or cortical dysplasia.",
      "disease_name": "TUBULIN, ALPHA-1A; TUBA1A"
    },
    {
      "title": "Hurler syndrome",
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurler_syndrome",
      "content": "[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: Hurler syndrome (Mucopolysaccharidosis type I-H, MPS-IH)\n\nGenetics: IDUA gene, autosomal recessive\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Progressive coarse facial features beginning in infancy (3\u20136 months)\n- Macrocephaly with prominent frontal bones and elongated skull\n- Flattened nasal bridge with chronic nasal discharge\n- Hypertelorism and proptosis (widely spaced, protruding eyes)\n- Large lips with characteristic habit of holding the jaw open\n- Skeletal abnormalities (dysostosis multiplex), including:\n  - Spine and hip deformities\n  - Joint stiffness\n  - Carpal tunnel syndrome\n- Growth disturbance: initially normal, then growth arrest by ~2 years, final height typically <4 feet\n- Multisystem involvement due to GAG storage (nervous system, skeletal system, eyes, heart)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n\n- Deficiency of alpha-L-iduronidase with lysosomal accumulation of dermatan sulfate and heparan sulfate\n- Early-onset progressive coarse facies plus severe skeletal disease (dysostosis multiplex) with marked growth arrest in early childhood\n- Classification as a mucopolysaccharidosis type I with severe (\u201cHurler\u201d) phenotype within the MPS I spectrum (vs Hurler\u2013Scheie, Scheie)\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n\n- Not X-linked (in contrast to clinically related Hunter syndrome/MPS II)\n\nUnique Constellation:\n\n- Autosomal recessive lysosomal storage disorder due to alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency, causing early-childhood onset of coarse facial features, macrocephaly with frontal bossing, chronic nasal discharge, protruding eyes, large lips with open-mouth posture, combined with progressive skeletal deformities (spine/hip), joint stiffness including carpal tunnel syndrome, and growth arrest by age ~2 years leading to short final stature.",
      "disease_name": "HURLER SYNDROME"
    },
    {
      "title": "Chopra-Amiel-Gordon Syndrome",
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chopra-Amiel-Gordon_Syndrome",
      "content": "[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: Chopra\u2013Amiel\u2013Gordon syndrome (CAGS) / ANKRD17\u2011related neurodevelopmental syndrome  \nGenetics: ANKRD17; autosomal dominant (heterozygous loss\u2011of\u2011function)\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Global developmental delay and/or intellectual disability  \n- Disproportionately severe speech delay  \n- Motor delay with hypotonia  \n- Gait and/or balance difficulties  \n- Epilepsy, often with absence seizures  \n- Behavioural issues: autism spectrum disorder, ADHD  \n- Distinctive craniofacial features:\n  - Triangular or elongated face  \n  - High anterior hairline  \n  - Almond\u2011shaped or deep\u2011set eyes  \n  - Full cheeks  \n  - Thick nasal alae with flared nostrils  \n  - Thin upper vermilion  \n  - Low\u2011set ears  \n- Less common craniofacial/skeletal findings:\n  - Cleft palate  \n  - Pierre Robin sequence  \n  - Scoliosis  \n- Ophthalmologic abnormalities: strabismus, refractive errors, microphthalmia  \n- Growth impairment  \n- Feeding difficulties  \n- Recurrent bacterial or viral infections  \n- Joint hypermobility  \n- Kidney anomalies  \n- Rare vascular involvement: ruptured cerebrovascular aneurysm (reported in at least one neonate)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n\n- Combination of global developmental delay/intellectual disability with markedly severe speech delay and absence seizures.  \n- Characteristic facial gestalt: triangular/elongated face with high anterior hairline, almond\u2011shaped or deep\u2011set eyes, full cheeks, thick nasal alae with flared nostrils, thin upper vermilion, and low\u2011set ears.  \n- Association of neurodevelopmental disorder with joint hypermobility, recurrent infections, and structural kidney anomalies in the setting of ANKRD17 loss\u2011of\u2011function.\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n\n- Not specified.\n\nUnique Constellation:\n\n- Neurodevelopmental disorder (global delay/ID, severe speech delay, autism/ADHD)  \n  + typical seizure type (frequent absence epilepsy)  \n  + hypotonia with gait/balance issues and joint hypermobility  \n  + distinctive craniofacial gestalt (triangular/elongated face, high anterior hairline, almond/deep\u2011set eyes, thick nasal alae with flared nostrils, thin upper vermilion, full cheeks, low\u2011set ears)  \n  + systemic involvement (recurrent infections, kidney anomalies, occasional cleft palate/Pierre Robin sequence, ophthalmologic anomalies).  \n\nThis multi-system pattern, particularly when coupled with absence seizures and the specified facial features, strongly points toward ANKRD17\u2011related neurodevelopmental syndrome among neurodevelopmental disorders with facial dysmorphism.",
      "disease_name": "CHOPRA-AMIEL-GORDON SYNDROME; CAGS"
    },
    {
      "title": "Schaaf\u2013Yang syndrome",
      "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schaaf%E2%80%93Yang_syndrome",
      "content": "[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: Schaaf\u2013Yang syndrome (SYS)\n\nGenetics: MAGEL2, autosomal dominant, paternally expressed (pathogenic variant on paternal chromosome 15q11.2)\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Intellectual disability / developmental delay (often borderline to mild)\n- Autism spectrum disorder / autistic behaviors / unusual behavior\n- Hypotonia in infancy\n- Feeding problems in infancy; failure to thrive; gastroesophageal reflux\n- Distal arthrogryposis / flexion contractures\n- Hypogonadism; external genital hypoplasia; undescended testes; lack of pubertal development\n- Visceral (truncal) obesity; type II diabetes (in some)\n- Facial dysmorphism: short nose, dense eyebrows, protruding jaw, facial shape abnormality, almond-shaped eyes (occasional), downturned mouth corners, thin nasal bridge, thin upper lip\n- Sleep apnea (including central sleep apnea)\n- Scoliosis, kyphosis\n- Chronic constipation\n- Eye problems, squint (strabismus)\n- Temperature regulation problems\n- Enlargement of cerebral ventricles\n- Atrial septal defect (occasional)\n- Hypothyroidism (occasional)\n- Seizures (occasional)\n- Abnormal dryness of the mouth\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s): \n- Combination of infant hypotonia with feeding difficulties plus distal arthrogryposis/flexion contractures.\n- Autism spectrum disorder and behavioral abnormalities superimposed on borderline/mild intellectual disability.\n- Paternally inherited (or de novo paternal-origin) MAGEL2 truncating mutation in the 15q11.2 region.\n\nKey Negative Finding(s): \n- Not specified in the text. (Notably, classic hyperphagia in early childhood is not listed among the main signs, which helps distinguish SYS clinically from Prader\u2013Willi syndrome, but this is not explicitly stated in the provided text.)\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Infantile hypotonia with significant feeding problems and distal arthrogryposis, evolving into a phenotype with autism spectrum disorder, mild intellectual disability, hypogonadism (undescended testes, external genital hypoplasia, absent puberty), visceral obesity, scoliosis/kyphosis, and characteristic but subtle facial features (short nose, dense eyebrows, protruding jaw), in the setting of a pathogenic MAGEL2 variant on the paternal chromosome\u2014this combination strongly points to Schaaf\u2013Yang syndrome over other 15q11\u2013q13 or hypotonia\u2013obesity\u2013autism syndromes.",
      "disease_name": "SCHAAF-YANG SYNDROME; SHFYNG"
    },
