    {
      "title": "The Phenotypic and Genotypic Spectrum of BRPF1-Related Disorder: 29 New Patients and Literature Review.",
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39837771/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: Intellectual Developmental Disorder with Dysmorphic Facies and Ptosis (IDDDFP)\n\nGenetics: BRPF1; Autosomal dominant\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Developmental delay  \n- Intellectual disability (predominantly mild to moderate)  \n- Dysmorphic facial features:\n  - Ptosis  \n  - Blepharophimosis  \n  - Broad nasal bridge  \n  - Palpebral edema  \n  - Laterally elongated eyebrows  \n  - Low-hanging columella  \n  - Hypertrichosis  \n- Structural brain abnormalities (e.g., agenesis of the corpus callosum)  \n- Ocular defects (non-specified, but recurrent)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s): \n- Combination of ptosis and blepharophimosis with a broad nasal bridge in the setting of developmental delay/ID  \n- BRPF1-related dysmorphic facies (ptosis + blepharophimosis + laterally elongated eyebrows + low-hanging columella)\n\nKey Negative Finding(s): \n- Not specified\n\nUnique Constellation: \n- Mild\u2013moderate intellectual disability plus characteristic periocular dysmorphism (ptosis, blepharophimosis, palpebral edema, laterally elongated eyebrows) and broad nasal bridge, often accompanied by corpus callosum abnormalities and ocular defects, strongly points to BRPF1-associated IDDDFP among neurodevelopmental syndromes with ptosis/blepharophimosis.",
      "disease_name": "INTELLECTUAL DEVELOPMENTAL DISORDER WITH DYSMORPHIC FACIES AND PTOSIS; IDDDFP"
    },
    {
      "title": {
        "i": "BRPF1",
        "#text": "Broadening the ocular phenotypic spectrum of ultra-rare  variants: report of two cases."
      },
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38590032/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: Intellectual Developmental Disorder with Dysmorphic Facies and Ptosis (IDDDFP)\n\nGenetics: Gene on 3p26-p25 (interacts with KAT6A/KAT6B); Heterozygous pathogenic variants; Autosomal dominant (by implication of heterozygosity)\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Global developmental delay  \n- Intellectual disability (often mild)  \n- Language delay  \n- Dysmorphic facial features (including \u201ctypical facies\u201d for the syndrome)  \n- Ptosis  \n- Ocular involvement:\n  - Strabismus  \n  - Amblyopia  \n  - Refractive errors  \n  - Subclinical optic neuropathy (bilateral, may be detected only on OCT)  \n- Chiari malformation type I (reported in at least one affected individual)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n\n- Combination of intellectual disability with ptosis and characteristic dysmorphic facies  \n- Subclinical optic neuropathy detectable on OCT in the context of this facial/ID phenotype  \n- Association with a gene encoding an epigenetic regulator interacting with KAT6A/KAT6B\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n\n- Overt/symptomatic optic neuropathy may be absent despite structural optic nerve involvement (i.e., optic neuropathy can be clinically silent)  \n\nUnique Constellation:\n\n- Global developmental delay/intellectual disability + language delay + dysmorphic facies with ptosis + ocular abnormalities (strabismus, amblyopia, refractive errors) + bilateral subclinical optic neuropathy (on OCT), occasionally with Chiari I malformation, strongly suggests Intellectual Developmental Disorder with Dysmorphic Facies and Ptosis due to heterozygous variants in the 3p26-p25 epigenetic regulator gene.",
      "disease_name": "INTELLECTUAL DEVELOPMENTAL DISORDER WITH DYSMORPHIC FACIES AND PTOSIS; IDDDFP"
    },
    {
      "title": "Integrated Genomic Approach: A Five Exon Intragenic Deletion in UNC80 Combines With a Novel Splice Variant to Cause IHPRF2 Syndrome in an Italian Family.",
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40801661/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: Infantile hypotonia, psychomotor retardation, and characteristic facies type 2 (IHPRF2)\n\nGenetics: UNC80; Autosomal recessive\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Neonatal hypotonia  \n- Severe global developmental delay / psychomotor retardation  \n- Major feeding difficulties, often requiring assisted nutrition  \n- Inability to speak (absent or severely limited speech)  \n- Inability to walk autonomously (severe motor impairment)  \n- Epilepsy  \n- Central sleep apnea  \n- Facial dysmorphism / characteristic facies  \n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s): \n- Combination of profound neonatal hypotonia, severe psychomotor retardation, and characteristic facial dysmorphism in the context of biallelic UNC80 variants  \n- Severe feeding difficulties necessitating assisted nutrition alongside global developmental arrest  \n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- Not specified  \n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Neonatal hypotonia + severe global developmental delay with absent speech and independent walking + feeding failure requiring assisted nutrition + epilepsy + central sleep apnea + characteristic facial dysmorphism in a child with biallelic UNC80 pathogenic variants strongly supports IHPRF2 over other causes of congenital hypotonia and developmental encephalopathy.",
      "disease_name": "HYPOTONIA, INFANTILE, WITH PSYCHOMOTOR RETARDATION AND CHARACTERISTIC FACIES 2; IHPRF2"
    },
