      },
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34594366/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: Infantile hypotonia with psychomotor retardation and characteristic facies 2 (IHPRF2)\n\nGenetics: UNC80, autosomal recessive\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n- Severe global developmental delay\n- Psychomotor retardation\n- Severe truncal hypotonia / infantile hypotonia\n- Poor or absent speech\n- Absent or limited walking abilities\n- Intellectual disability\n- Characteristic facies (not further detailed in text)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n- Combination of infantile/early-onset severe truncal hypotonia with marked global developmental delay\n- Very poor or absent speech together with absent or markedly limited independent walking\n- Association with pathogenic biallelic variants in UNC80\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- Not specified\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Early-onset severe hypotonia + profound psychomotor delay + absent/near-absent speech + inability or severe limitation in walking, in the context of biallelic UNC80 variants, strongly supports the diagnosis of IHPRF2 over other causes of congenital hypotonia and global developmental delay.",
      "disease_name": "HYPOTONIA, INFANTILE, WITH PSYCHOMOTOR RETARDATION AND CHARACTERISTIC FACIES 2; IHPRF2"
    },
    {
      "title": "Whole exome sequencing revealed mutations in FBXL4, UNC80, and ADK in Thai patients with severe intellectual disabilities.",
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30771478/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: Encephalomyopathic mitochondrial DNA depletion syndrome-13 (MTDPS13)  \nGenetics: FBXL4, Autosomal recessive  \n\nKey Phenotypes:\n- Intellectual disability\n- Hypotonia\n- Lactic acidosis\n- Encephalomyopathic mitochondrial disease features (implied by syndrome name)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n- Combination of hypotonia with lactic acidosis in the context of intellectual disability\n- Encephalomyopathic presentation associated with mitochondrial DNA depletion\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- Not specified\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Intellectual disability + hypotonia + lactic acidosis strongly suggests FBXL4-related MTDPS13 among causes of syndromic ID with metabolic acidosis.\n\n\n---\n\nDisease: Infantile hypotonia with psychomotor retardation and characteristic facies-2 (IHPRF2)  \nGenetics: UNC80, Autosomal recessive  \n\nKey Phenotypes:\n- Intellectual disability (psychomotor retardation)\n- Infantile/early hypotonia (implied by disorder name)\n- Growth failure\n- Characteristic facies (implied by disorder name, though not detailed here)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n- Combination of infantile hypotonia and psychomotor retardation with characteristic facial appearance due to UNC80 variants\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- Not specified\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Intellectual disability with early hypotonia and growth failure in the setting of UNC80 mutations and characteristic facies helps distinguish IHPRF2 from other hypotonia\u2013ID syndromes.\n\n\n---\n\nDisease: Adenosine kinase deficiency (hypermethioninemia due to ADK deficiency)  \nGenetics: ADK, Autosomal recessive  \n\nKey Phenotypes:\n- Intellectual disability\n- Seizures\n- Diarrhea\n- Hypoglycemia\n- Hypermethioninemia (biochemical hallmark, implied by description)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n- Hypermethioninemia due to adenosine kinase deficiency\n- Neurologic manifestations (ID, seizures) with metabolic abnormalities\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- Not specified\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Intellectual disability + seizures + hypoglycemia + diarrhea in the context of hypermethioninemia is strongly suggestive of ADK deficiency among metabolic causes of syndromic ID.",
      "disease_name": "HYPOTONIA, INFANTILE, WITH PSYCHOMOTOR RETARDATION AND CHARACTERISTIC FACIES 2; IHPRF2"
    },
    {
      "title": "Speech and Language Development of Two Brothers With Bainbridge-Ropers Syndrome: Phenotypic and Bioinformatic Support for a Cerebellar ASXL3 Hypothesis.",
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40891523/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: Bainbridge-Ropers syndrome (BRPS)\n\nGenetics: ASXL3; Autosomal dominant (typically de novo, including possible parental germline mosaicism)\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Global developmental delay and motor delay\n- Hypotonia\n- Intellectual disability (variable; can be mild to moderate, or more severe)\n- Autism spectrum disorder/Autistic features\n- Seizures\n- Feeding difficulties\n- Craniofacial dysmorphism\n- Skeletal anomalies\n- Marked speech and language impairment\n- Difficulty with verbal communication in all affected individuals\n- Developmental coordination disorder, compatible with cerebellar dysfunction\n- Childhood apraxia of speech (in some individuals)\n- Oral apraxia (in some individuals)\n- Language disorder (in some individuals)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n\n- Universal difficulty with verbal communication in affected individuals, often severe, with apraxia of speech or oral apraxia as a prominent component.\n- Combination of developmental coordination disorder (cerebellar-type motor discoordination) with significant speech motor planning deficits (CAS/oral apraxia).\n- ASXL3-related neurodevelopmental phenotype with craniofacial and skeletal anomalies plus hypotonia and feeding difficulties.\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n\n- Not specified.\n\nUnique Constellation:\n\n- ASXL3 pathogenic variant with:  \n  \u2022 Early feeding difficulties and hypotonia  \n  \u2022 Global developmental delay with motor discoordination consistent with cerebellar dysfunction  \n  \u2022 Marked impairment of speech and language with childhood apraxia of speech and/or oral apraxia and universal difficulty with verbal communication  \n  \u2022 Intellectual disability and/or autism, plus craniofacial and skeletal anomalies  \n\n  This particular clustering of severe speech motor planning disorder, cerebellar-type coordination disorder, and ASXL3-associated dysmorphism strongly points toward Bainbridge-Ropers syndrome versus other causes of global developmental delay and autism.",
      "disease_name": "INTELLECTUAL DEVELOPMENTAL DISORDER WITH SPEECH DELAY AND DYSMORPHIC FACIES; IDDSDF"
    },
    {
      "title": "Case report of paroxysmal dystonia in a child with KBG syndrome: Expansion of the phenotype and utility of whole exome sequencing.",
      "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40760574/",
      "content": "[Source: PubMed] Disease: KBG syndrome  \nGenetics: ANKRD11, autosomal dominant\n\nKey Phenotypes:\n\n- Neurodevelopmental:\n  - Global developmental delay\n  - Autism spectrum disorder / neurodevelopmental disorder\n- Craniofacial/dental:\n  - Macrodontia\n  - Distinctive facial features (not further specified in text)\n- Neurologic:\n  - Spastic diplegia\n  - Paroxysmal/episodic unilateral dystonic spells (paroxysmal dystonia)\n- Auditory:\n  - Sensorineural hearing loss (may be profound; in this case potentially also influenced by CDH23 variants)\n- Systemic:\n  - \u201cRange of systemic manifestations\u201d (not detailed in this text)\n\nDifferentiating Features:\n\nHallmark(s):\n- Macrodontia in combination with distinctive facial features and developmental delay\n- Pathogenic variants in ANKRD11 with autosomal dominant inheritance pattern\n\nKey Negative Finding(s):\n- Not specified in the text\n\nUnique Constellation:\n- Developmental delay / autism spectrum disorder\n- Macrodontia and distinctive facial features\n- Spastic diplegia with paroxysmal unilateral dystonic spells (dystonia proposed as an underrecognized feature)\n- Sensorineural hearing loss  \nThis combination, especially when paired with an ANKRD11 pathogenic variant, strongly points toward KBG syndrome among neurodevelopmental disorders with movement abnormalities.",
      "disease_name": "INTELLECTUAL DEVELOPMENTAL DISORDER WITH SPEECH DELAY AND DYSMORPHIC FACIES; IDDSDF"
    },
    {
