[Source: Wikipedia] Disease: Hurler syndrome (Mucopolysaccharidosis type I-H, MPS-IH)

Genetics: IDUA gene, autosomal recessive

Key Phenotypes:

- Progressive coarse facial features beginning in infancy (3–6 months)
- Macrocephaly with prominent frontal bones and elongated skull
- Flattened nasal bridge with chronic nasal discharge
- Hypertelorism and proptosis (widely spaced, protruding eyes)
- Large lips with characteristic habit of holding the jaw open
- Skeletal abnormalities (dysostosis multiplex), including:
  - Spine and hip deformities
  - Joint stiffness
  - Carpal tunnel syndrome
- Growth disturbance: initially normal, then growth arrest by ~2 years, final height typically <4 feet
- Multisystem involvement due to GAG storage (nervous system, skeletal system, eyes, heart)

Differentiating Features:

Hallmark(s):

- Deficiency of alpha-L-iduronidase with lysosomal accumulation of dermatan sulfate and heparan sulfate
- Early-onset progressive coarse facies plus severe skeletal disease (dysostosis multiplex) with marked growth arrest in early childhood
- Classification as a mucopolysaccharidosis type I with severe (“Hurler”) phenotype within the MPS I spectrum (vs Hurler–Scheie, Scheie)

Key Negative Finding(s):

- Not X-linked (in contrast to clinically related Hunter syndrome/MPS II)

Unique Constellation:

- Autosomal recessive lysosomal storage disorder due to alpha-L-iduronidase deficiency, causing early-childhood onset of coarse facial features, macrocephaly with frontal bossing, chronic nasal discharge, protruding eyes, large lips with open-mouth posture, combined with progressive skeletal deformities (spine/hip), joint stiffness including carpal tunnel syndrome, and growth arrest by age ~2 years leading to short final stature.
