    {
      "disease_name": "Witteveen-Kolk syndrome (WITKOS, SIN3A-related neurodevelopmental disorder)",
      "Correctness": true,
      "PatientSummary": "Male patient with global developmental delay, mild intellectual disability, delayed walking and speech, hypotonia, failure to thrive and feeding difficulties, seizures, and multiple structural brain abnormalities (corpus callosum hypoplasia, simplified gyral pattern, delayed myelination, retrocerebellar cyst). He has craniofacial dysmorphism including low-set protruding ears, downslanted palpebral fissures, hypertelorism, ptosis, micrognathia, narrow mouth with trismus, and plagiocephaly, along with obstructive sleep apnea and laryngomalacia. Additional findings include micropenis and mild digital anomalies (tapered fingers, narrow nails).",
      "DiagnosisAnalysis": "Evidence FOR Witteveen–Kolk syndrome (WITKOS):\n\n1. Core neurodevelopmental phenotype\n- The patient has global developmental delay, mild intellectual disability, delayed walking, and delayed speech and language. WITKOS is consistently described as a neurodevelopmental disorder with global developmental delay and intellectual disability [24], [25]. The literature also emphasizes motor developmental delay and intellectual developmental delay as key features [25].\n- Hypotonia is present in this child and is a listed feature in infants with WITKOS/15q24.1–q24.2 deletions [25].\n\n2. Growth and feeding\n- The patient has failure to thrive and feeding difficulties. WITKOS case series describe growth delay/short stature and feeding difficulties in infancy as part of the syndrome [24], [25]. Although the wording in the report here is “growth delay / short stature” rather than explicit “failure to thrive,” failure to thrive with feeding problems is compatible with that growth phenotype.\n\n3. Craniofacial dysmorphism\n- The child has low-set ears, protruding ears, downslanted palpebral fissures, hypertelorism, ptosis, micrognathia, narrow mouth, and plagiocephaly. WITKOS is characterized as a syndromic disorder with facial dysmorphism [3], [24]. More detailed descriptions include wide forehead and low nasal bridge with low-set ears as characteristic features [25]; the patient matches at least the low-set ears component, and has a clearly abnormal craniofacial gestalt, which is required but not highly specific in its fine details.\n\n4. Brain abnormalities\n- The patient has hypoplasia of the corpus callosum, simplified gyral pattern, delayed CNS myelination, and a retrocerebellar cyst. WITKOS is reported to include structural brain abnormalities as part of its core phenotype [24]. The presence of multiple malformations (callosal hypoplasia, cortical and myelination abnormalities) fits the notion of a syndromic neurodevelopmental disorder with brain abnormalities involving SIN3A [24], [25].\n\n5. Genital / endocrine\n- The patient has micropenis. Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism has been reported in at least some WITKOS patients [23]. While micropenis is not listed explicitly in the brief summaries, it is a typical manifestation of hypogonadotropic hypogonadism in males, so this is pathophysiologically very compatible with the reported endocrine involvement in WITKOS [23].\n\n6. Multi-system, syndromic presentation\n- WITKOS is recognized as a syndromic neurodevelopmental disorder with multi-system involvement [23], [24]. This patient has neurologic, craniofacial, growth/feeding, respiratory (obstructive sleep apnea, laryngomalacia), and genital involvement, which fits a broad multi-system syndrome in line with WITKOS.\n\n7. Overall alignment with SIN3A/15q24 microdeletion profile\n- The proposed diagnosis is based on similarity to 15q24 microdeletion phenotypes characterized by neurodevelopmental delay, growth retardation, facial dysmorphism, and genital anomalies [3], [25]. The patient presents exactly this combination: neurodevelopmental delay/intellectual disability, failure to thrive/growth issues, dysmorphic facial features, and micropenis.\n\nEvidence AGAINST or requiring caution:\n\n1. Missing hallmark genetic evidence\n- The strongest hallmark of WITKOS is a heterozygous SIN3A loss-of-function variant or a 15q24 microdeletion including SIN3A [3], [23], [24], [25]. In this case description, no genetic result is provided. Without documented SIN3A haploinsufficiency or 15q24 involvement, the diagnosis remains provisional. However, the task here is to evaluate phenotypic fit rather than confirm molecular diagnosis.\n\n2. Short stature/growth delay not explicitly stated\n- Literature emphasizes short stature or growth delay as a typical feature [3], [24], [25]. The patient is reported to have “failure to thrive” but not explicitly “short stature.” Failure to thrive usually implies poor weight gain and can be associated with linear growth impairment; nonetheless, if the child’s length/height were normal, that would weaken the match. The absence of explicit short stature is a mild limitation but not a strong contradiction.\n\n3. Limited detail on the classic WITKOS facial gestalt\n- Published descriptions mention a characteristic facial appearance including wide forehead and low nasal bridge along with low-set ears [25]. In this case we only know about low-set/protruding ears, hypertelorism, ptosis, downslanted palpebral fissures, micrognathia, and narrow mouth. While clearly abnormal, this is not specific enough to confirm the classic gestalt, and wide forehead/low nasal bridge are not documented. However, given documented phenotypic heterogeneity and variable craniofacial features [23], [24], this does not weigh heavily against the diagnosis.\n\n4. Some uncommon or not specifically reported features\n- The child has laryngomalacia, obstructive sleep apnea, trismus, impaired mastication, simplified gyral pattern, retrocerebellar cyst, and plagiocephaly. These are not specifically mentioned in the brief WITKOS literature summaries provided. Many of these findings (especially airway anomalies and specific brain malformation subtypes) may be underreported or fall within the broader category of \"brain abnormalities\" and syndromic involvement. Given the documented phenotypic heterogeneity of WITKOS [23], their absence from limited case descriptions should not be interpreted as true contradictions.\n\n5. Behavioral/psychiatric description missing\n- Some case reports highlight behavioral and psychiatric problems as a prominent component of WITKOS [24]. In this child, autistic behavior is explicitly absent, and there is no mention of other behavioral issues. Behavioral manifestations are age-dependent and variable, and their absence in the phenotype list is not strong evidence against the diagnosis, especially in a young child.\n\nSynthesis and weighting of evidence:\n\n- Strongly supportive features include global developmental delay and mild intellectual disability, motor delay, hypotonia, feeding difficulties, and a syndromic craniofacial phenotype, all of which are central in WITKOS descriptions [24], [25]. The presence of multiple structural brain abnormalities aligns with the described “brain abnormalities” in WITKOS [24] and supports a syndromic neurodevelopmental disorder rather than an isolated delay.\n- The growth problem (failure to thrive) plausibly reflects the growth delay/short stature commonly seen in WITKOS [24], [25], even if height is not explicitly reported. Micropenis fits well with the hypogonadotropic hypogonadism described in some WITKOS patients [23], reinforcing the match to a SIN3A-related endocrine/gonadal phenotype.\n- The craniofacial features overlap partially with published descriptions (notably low-set ears [25]) and demonstrate a distinct dysmorphic gestalt, as expected in WITKOS [3], while acknowledging that the fine details differ and the classic “wide forehead/low nasal bridge” combination is not explicitly documented. Given the recognized phenotypic variability and atypical presentations in WITKOS [23], the partial facial overlap is acceptable.\n- There are no features here that clearly contradict WITKOS or strongly point toward another specific single-gene syndrome; instead, the pattern remains that of a multi-system neurodevelopmental disorder with brain malformations and genital anomaly, which is compatible with a pathogenic variant in SIN3A/15q24.\n\nOn balance, the phenotype shows a strong and specific overlap with the core WITKOS/15q24 microdeletion profile—developmental delay, hypotonia, syndromic facial dysmorphism, feeding/growth issues, brain abnormalities, and micropenis consistent with hypogonadotropic hypogonadism—in the context of reported phenotypic heterogeneity. While molecular confirmation is essential in real practice, the phenotypic pattern is sufficiently compelling that Witteveen–Kolk syndrome should remain a prioritized and plausible diagnosis rather than be deprioritized.\n",
      "references": [
        "Wikipedia – Witteveen–Kolk syndrome (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Witteveen%E2%80%93Kolk_syndrome): “Witteveen–Kolk syndrome… is a genetic disorder characterized by developmental delay, intellectual disability, short stature, and facial dysmorphism… It is associated with heterozygous loss-of-function variants or deletions involving SIN3A at chromosome 15q24.”",
        "PubMed – Report on Witteveen-Kolk syndrome caused by large fragment deletion in the 15q24.1–q24.2 region in infants with early onset and literature review (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40336075/): “Patients with Witteveen-Kolk syndrome present with intellectual developmental delay, motor developmental delay, growth delay/short stature, hypotonia, and feeding difficulties in infancy.”",
        "PubMed – Report on Witteveen-Kolk syndrome caused by large fragment deletion in the 15q24.1–q24.2 region in infants with early onset and literature review (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40336075/): “Characteristic craniofacial features include a wide forehead, low nasal bridge, and low-set ears… The syndrome results from haploinsufficiency of SIN3A due to heterozygous loss-of-function variants or deletions in 15q24.1–q24.2.”",
        "PubMed – Personalized Treatment in Rare Genetic Syndromes: A Case-Report in Witteveen-Kolk Syndrome (SIN3A) (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41245232/): “Witteveen-Kolk syndrome is a neurodevelopmental disorder caused by heterozygous pathogenic variants in SIN3A… Clinical features include global developmental problems, intellectual disability, short stature, facial dysmorphism and brain abnormalities.”",
        "PubMed – Personalized Treatment in Rare Genetic Syndromes: A Case-Report in Witteveen-Kolk Syndrome (SIN3A) (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41245232/): “The disorder is characterized by developmental delay and intellectual disability associated with a syndromic presentation, including facial dysmorphism and structural brain abnormalities, often accompanied by behavioral and psychiatric problems.”",
        "PubMed – Two Unrelated Witteveen-Kolk Syndrome Patients Presenting with Unusual Clinical Features: Dual Diagnosis and Atypical Rare Manifestation (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41409308/): “Witteveen-Kolk syndrome (WITKOS) is an autosomal dominant neurodevelopmental disorder caused by heterozygous loss-of-function variants or microdeletions involving SIN3A at 15q24.”",
        "PubMed – Two Unrelated Witteveen-Kolk Syndrome Patients Presenting with Unusual Clinical Features: Dual Diagnosis and Atypical Rare Manifestation (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41409308/): “The clinical phenotype is syndromic and variable… In some patients, hypogonadotropic hypogonadism has been reported, expanding the endocrine spectrum of Witteveen-Kolk syndrome.”"
